*'''(1992)''' ISI engineered the takeover of Afghanistan by the hard-line Islamic [[Taliban]] regime after the fall of the Communist government in Kabul in 1992.

*'''(1994)''' The Taliban regime that the ISI supported after 1994 to suppress warlord fighting and in hopes of bringing stability to Afghanistan proved [[Taliban#Life under the Taliban regime|too rigid]] in its Islamic interpretations and too fond of the [[Al-Qaeda]] based on its soil. Despite receiving large sums of aid from Pakistan, the Taliban leader [[Mohammed Omar|Mullah Omar]] is reported to have insulted a visiting delegation of Saudi Prince Sultan and an ISI general asking that the Taliban turn over bin Laden to Saudi Arabia.<ref>Rashid, Ahmed, ''Taliban: Militant Islam, Oil, and Fundamentalism in Central Asia''. Yale University Press, (2000), p.138, 231 </ref> Following the 9/11 attack on the United States by Al-Qaeda, Pakistan felt it necessary to cooperate with the US and the [[United Islamic Front for the Salvation of Afghanistan|Northern Alliance]] in a [[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|war]] against the Taliban.

